Functional morphology: The functional morphology is essentially similar to other thyasirids that are primarily chemosymbiotic and strongly associated with chemosynthetic settings (
Oliver & Sellanes 2005
). The gills are thick and fleshy and of Dufour Type 3 (
Dufour 2005
). The foot is vermiform and the lateral body pouches are large and multilobed. Stable isotopic ratios are in the range of other symbiotic chemosyntheticbased bivalves hosting sulfide-oxydizing symbionts (CF Rodrigues unpublished results).

The unusual condition of the holotype suggests that the bacteria were lost from the gills and that digestion had slowed or ceased resulting in morbidity. The mortality of bivalves has been already studied and sulphide deprivation, sulphide toxicity, and disease were indicated as possible agents of mortality on the system (
Mills et al. 2005
).
